# CaptureKit C++ Coding Standards and Best Practices

## Core Principles

### 0. Don't sweat the small stuff
- Don't enforce personal tastes or obsolete practices
- Say only what needs saying
- Focus on what matters for code quality and maintainability

### 1. Compile cleanly at high warning levels
- Use compiler's highest warning level
- Require clean (warning-free) builds
- Understand all warnings
- Eliminate warnings by changing code, not reducing warning level

### 2. Use automated build system
- One-action build system that builds entire project
- No manual intervention required
- CMake with presets for different configurations

### 3. Use version control system
- Check in frequently after unit tests pass
- Ensure checked-in code doesn't break build
- Never keep files checked out for long periods

### 4. Invest in code reviews
- More eyes help make more quality
- Show your code and read others'
- Learn and benefit from peer review

## Design Style

### 5. Give one entity one cohesive responsibility
- Each entity (variable, class, function, namespace, module, library) should have one well-defined responsibility
- As entity grows, scope increases but responsibility should not diverge

### 6. Correctness, simplicity, and clarity come first
- KISS (Keep It Simple Software)
- Correct is better than fast
- Simple is better than complex
- Clear is better than cute
- Safe is better than insecure

### 7. Know when and how to code for scalability
- Keep eye on asymptotic complexity
- Algorithms should take predictable, preferably linear time
- Focus on big-Oh complexity over micro-optimizations

### 8. Don't optimize prematurely
- First rule: Don't do it
- Second rule (experts only): Don't do it yet
- Measure twice, optimize once

### 9. Don't pessimize prematurely
- Use efficient design patterns that flow naturally
- No harder to write than pessimized alternatives
- This is not premature optimization

### 10. Minimize global and shared data
- Avoid shared data, especially global data
- Shared data increases coupling, reduces maintainability and performance

### 11. Hide information
- Don't expose internal information from entities providing abstraction

### 12. Know when and how to code for concurrency
- Minimize sharing objects where possible
- Share the right ones safely

### 13. Ensure resources are owned by objects
- Use explicit RAII and smart pointers
- Never allocate more than one resource in single statement
- Pass raw resources immediately to owning objects

## Coding Style

### 14. Prefer compile- and link-time errors to run-time errors
- Use compiler to check invariants during compilation
- Run-time checks are control- and data-dependent

### 15. Use const proactively
- Make const your default choice
- Immutable values are easier to understand, track, and reason about
- Don't cast away const except to call const-incorrect functions

### 16. Avoid macros
- Macros are the bluntest instrument of C++ abstraction facilities
- Hard to tame, marching to their own beat
- Avoid them

### 17. Avoid magic numbers
- Use symbolic names and expressions instead
- Not self-explanatory and complicate maintenance

### 18. Declare variables as locally as possible
- Variables introduce state
- Deal with as little state as possible
- Keep lifetimes as short as possible

### 19. Always initialize variables
- Uninitialized variables are common source of bugs
- Initialize upon definition

### 20. Avoid long functions and deep nesting
- Short is better than long
- Flat is better than deep
- Often solved by better refactoring

### 21. Avoid initialization dependencies across compilation units
- Namespace-level objects in different compilation units should never depend on each other
- Initialization order is undefined

### 22. Minimize definitional dependencies
- Don't #include definition when forward declaration will do
- Avoid cyclic dependencies
- Cyclic dependencies work against modularity

### 23. Make header files self-sufficient
- Each header should be compilable standalone
- Include any headers its contents depend upon

### 24. Always write internal #include guards
- Use #pragma once for all header files
- Never write external #include guards

## Functions and Operators

### 25. Take parameters appropriately
- Distinguish among input, output, and input/output parameters
- Between value and reference parameters
- Take them appropriately

### 26. Preserve natural semantics for overloaded operators
- Overload operators only for good reason
- Preserve natural semantics
- If difficult, you might be misusing operator overloading

### 27. Prefer canonical forms of arithmetic and assignment operators
- When defining binary arithmetic operators, provide assignment versions
- Write to minimize duplication and maximize efficiency

### 28. Prefer canonical form of ++ and --
- Define operator++ and operator-- to mimic built-in counterparts
- Prefer prefix versions if you don't need original value

### 29. Consider overloading to avoid implicit type conversions
- Provide overloaded functions with signatures that match common argument types exactly
- Won't cause conversions

### 30. Avoid overloading &&, ||, or , (comma)
- Built-in versions enjoy special compiler treatment
- Overloading makes them ordinary functions with different semantics
- Sure way to introduce subtle bugs

### 31. Don't write code that depends on function argument evaluation order
- Order is unspecified
- Don't rely on specific ordering

## Class Design and Inheritance

### 32. Be clear what kind of class you're writing
- Know which kind you are writing
- Different kinds have different blueprints

### 33. Prefer minimal classes to monolithic classes
- Small classes are easier to write, get right, test, and use
- More likely to be usable in variety of situations
- Avoid kitchen-sink classes

### 34. Prefer composition to inheritance
- Inheritance is second-tightest coupling relationship
- Tight coupling is undesirable
- Prefer composition unless inheritance truly benefits design

### 35. Avoid inheriting from classes not designed to be base classes
- Classes meant to be standalone obey different blueprint than base classes
- Serious design error
- To add behavior, prefer non-member functions
- To add state, prefer composition

### 36. Prefer providing abstract interfaces
- Abstract interfaces help focus on getting abstraction right
- Without muddling with implementation or state management details
- Design hierarchies that implement abstract interfaces

### 37. Public inheritance is substitutability
- Inherit not to reuse, but to be reused
- Allows base class pointer/reference to refer to derived class object
- Without destroying code correctness

### 38. Practice safe overriding
- Preserve substitutability when overriding virtual functions
- Observe pre- and post-conditions
- Don't change default arguments
- Prefer explicitly redeclaring overrides as virtual

### 39. Consider making virtual functions nonpublic
- In base classes with high cost of change
- Prefer public functions nonvirtual
- Prefer virtual functions private or protected

### 40. Avoid providing implicit conversions
- Can often do more damage than good
- Think twice before providing implicit conversions
- Prefer explicit conversions

### 41. Make data members private
- Except in behaviorless aggregates (C-style structs)
- Keep data members private
- Avoid mixes of public and nonpublic data

### 42. Don't give away your internals
- Avoid returning handles to internal data
- Clients won't uncontrollably modify state

### 43. Pimpl judiciously
- Make private members truly invisible using Pimpl idiom
- Implement compiler firewalls
- Increase information hiding

### 44. Prefer writing nonmember nonfriend functions
- Where possible, prefer making functions nonmember nonfriends
- Avoid membership fees

### 45. Always provide new and delete together
- They're a package deal
- Every class-specific overload must be accompanied by corresponding overload

### 46. Provide all standard forms of new
- If defining any overload, provide all three: plain, in-place, and nothrow
- Don't hide good news

## Construction, Destruction, and Copying

### 47. Define and initialize member variables in same order
- Member variables always initialized in order declared in class definition
- Constructor initialization list order is ignored
- Don't confusingly specify different order

### 48. Prefer initialization to assignment in constructors
- Prevents needless run-time work
- Takes same amount of typing

### 49. Avoid calling virtual functions in constructors and destructors
- Virtual functions don't behave virtually inside constructors/destructors
- Direct/indirect call to unimplemented pure virtual function results in undefined behavior

### 50. Make base class destructors public and virtual, or protected and nonvirtual
- If deletion through base pointer should be allowed: public and virtual
- Otherwise: protected and nonvirtual

### 51. Destructors, deallocation, and swap never fail
- Everything they attempt shall succeed
- Never allow error to be reported
- Types with throwing destructors forbidden from use with standard library

### 52. Copy and destroy consistently
- If defining any of copy constructor, copy assignment, or destructor
- You might need to define one or both of others

### 53. Explicitly enable or disable copying
- Knowingly choose among compiler-generated, writing own, or explicitly disabling
- Copy consciously

### 54. Avoid slicing
- Object slicing is automatic, invisible, and likely to bring polymorphic designs to halt
- Consider disabling copy constructor and assignment operator in base classes
- Supply virtual Clone member function instead

### 55. Prefer canonical form of assignment
- Nonvirtual with specific signature
- Your assignment

### 56. Provide no-fail swap
- Consider providing swap function to efficiently and infallibly swap internals
- Handy for implementing idioms
- Provides guaranteed commit function

## Namespaces and Modules

### 57. Keep type and nonmember function interface in same namespace
- Nonmember functions designed to be part of class X interface
- Must be defined in same namespace as X
- To be called correctly

### 58. Keep types and functions in separate namespaces
- Unless specifically intended to work together
- Isolate types from unintentional argument-dependent lookup
- Encourage intentional ADL

### 59. Don't write namespace usings in header file or before #include
- Never write using declaration or directive before #include
- In header files, don't write namespace-level using directives
- Explicitly namespace-qualify all names

### 60. Avoid allocating and deallocating memory in different modules
- Makes program fragile by creating subtle long-distance dependency
- Must be compiled with same compiler version and flags
- Module allocating memory had better still be loaded when deallocation happens

### 61. Don't define entities with linkage in header file
- Entities with linkage have memory allocated for them
- Results in either link-time errors or memory waste
- Put all entities with linkage in implementation files

### 62. Don't allow exceptions to propagate across module boundaries
- No ubiquitous binary standard for C++ exception handling
- Don't allow exceptions to propagate between code unless you control compiler
- Don't let exceptions propagate across module/subsystem boundaries

### 63. Use sufficiently portable types in module interface
- Don't allow type to appear in external interface unless all clients understand it correctly
- Use highest level of abstraction clients can understand

## Templates and Genericity

### 64. Blend static and dynamic polymorphism judiciously
- Static and dynamic polymorphism are complementary
- Understand tradeoffs
- Use each for what it's best at
- Mix them to get best of both worlds

### 65. Customize intentionally and explicitly
- Intentional is better than accidental
- Explicit is better than implicit
- Provide points of customization knowingly and correctly
- Document them clearly

### 66. Don't specialize function templates
- Avoid trying to write specialization
- Write overload instead
- Put it in namespace of type(s) overload is designed for

### 67. Don't write unintentionally nongeneric code
- Commit to abstractions, not to details
- Use most generic and abstract means to implement functionality

## Error Handling and Exceptions

### 68. Assert liberally
- Use assert liberally to document assumptions internal to module
- Must always be true and represent programming errors
- Ensure assertions don't perform side effects

### 69. Establish rational error handling policy
- Develop practical, consistent, and rational policy early in design
- Stick to it strictly
- Include: identification, severity, detection, propagation, handling, reporting

### 70. Distinguish between errors and non-errors
- A function is unit of work
- Failures should be viewed as errors based on impact on functions
- Exclude internal programming errors (use assertions)

### 71. Design and write error-safe code
- Give strongest safety guarantee that won't penalize callers who don't need it
- Always give at least basic guarantee
- Ensure errors always leave program in valid state
- Prefer strong guarantee (rollback or commit)
- Prefer no-fail guarantee when possible

### 72. Prefer exceptions to report errors
- Prefer using exceptions over error codes
- Use status codes for errors when exceptions cannot be used
- Use other methods when recovery is impossible or not required

### 73. Throw by value, catch by reference
- Throw exceptions by value (not pointer)
- Catch them by reference (usually to const)
- When rethrowing, prefer just throw; to throw e;

### 74. Report, handle, and translate errors appropriately
- Report errors at point they are detected and identified
- Handle or translate each error at nearest level that can do it correctly

### 75. Avoid exception specifications
- Don't write exception specifications unless forced to
- Take exception to these specifications

## STL: Containers

### 76. Use vector by default
- Using "right container" is great if you have good reason
- Otherwise, write vector and keep going
- You did the right thing

### 77. Use vector and string instead of arrays
- Avoid implementing array abstractions with C-style arrays
- Pointer arithmetic and memory management primitives
- Makes life easier, safer and more scalable software

### 78. Use vector to exchange data with non-C++ APIs
- vector and string::c_str are gateway to communicate with non-C++ APIs
- Don't assume iterators are pointers
- Use &*iter to get address of element

### 79. Store only values and smart pointers in containers
- Containers assume they contain value-like types
- Including value types, smart pointers, and iterators

### 80. Prefer push_back to other ways of expanding sequence
- If you don't need to care about insert position
- Other means can be vastly slower and less clear

### 81. Prefer range operations to single-element operations
- When adding elements to sequence containers
- Prefer range operations instead of series of single-element calls
- Generally easier to write, read, and more efficient

### 82. Use accepted idioms to shrink capacity and erase elements
- Use "swap trick" to shed excess capacity
- Use erase-remove idiom to erase elements

## STL: Algorithms

### 83. Use checked STL implementation
- Safety first
- Use checked STL implementation even if only available for one platform
- Even if only used during pre-release testing

### 84. Prefer algorithm calls to handwritten loops
- For very simple loops, handwritten loops can be simplest and most efficient
- Algorithm calls can be more expressive and maintainable
- Less error-prone and as efficient
- Consider writing custom function objects

### 85. Use right STL search algorithm
- Search "just enough"
- Use find/find_if or count/count_if for unsorted ranges
- Use lower_bound, upper_bound, equal_range for sorted ranges

### 86. Use right STL sort algorithm
- Sort "just enough"
- Understand what each sorting algorithm does
- Use cheapest algorithm that does what you need

### 87. Make predicates pure functions
- Predicate result depends only on arguments
- Don't allow predicates to hold or access state affecting result
- Prefer to make operator() const member function

### 88. Prefer function objects over functions
- Objects plug in better than functions
- Prefer passing function objects, not functions, to algorithms
- Comparers for associative containers must be function objects
- Function objects are adaptable and typically faster

### 89. Write function objects correctly
- Be cheap, be adaptable
- Design to be values that are cheap to copy
- Make them adaptable by inheriting from unary_function or binary_function

## Type Safety

### 90. Avoid type switching; prefer polymorphism
- Avoid switching on type of object to customize behavior
- Use templates and virtual functions
- Let types decide their behavior

### 91. Rely on types, not on representations
- Don't make assumptions about how objects are exactly represented in memory
- Let types decide how objects are written to and read from memory

### 92. Avoid using reinterpret_cast
- Don't try to force compiler to reinterpret bits of one type as another
- Opposite of maintaining type safety
- Not guaranteed to do anything in particular

### 93. Avoid using static_cast on pointers
- Pointers to dynamic objects don't static cast
- Safe alternatives: dynamic_cast, refactoring, redesigning

### 94. Avoid casting away const
- Sometimes results in undefined behavior
- Staple of poor programming style even when legal

### 95. Don't use C-style casts
- Have different and often dangerous semantics depending on context
- All disguised behind single syntax
- C++-style casts help guard against unexpected errors

### 96. Don't memcpy or memcmp non-PODs
- Don't try to X-ray objects
- Don't use memcpy and memcmp for anything more structured than raw memory

### 97. Don't use unions to reinterpret representation
- Can be abused into obtaining "cast without a cast"
- More insidious and less predictable than reinterpret_cast

### 98. Don't use varargs (ellipsis)
- Dangerous carryover from C
- Avoid varargs
- Use higher-level C++ constructs and libraries instead

### 99. Don't use invalid objects or unsafe functions
- Both wreak havoc on program's health
- Don't use expired medicines

### 100. Don't treat arrays polymorphically
- Treating arrays polymorphically is gross type error
- Compiler will probably remain silent about it
- Don't fall into the trap

## Project-Specific Rules

### CaptureKit Specific Standards
- Use C++20 features appropriately
- Follow Qt6 best practices for UI components
- Use RAII for all resource management
- Implement proper error handling for capture and encoding operations
- Use smart pointers for memory management
- Follow the established module structure
- Write comprehensive tests for all new functionality
- Document public APIs thoroughly
- Use consistent naming conventions (snake_case for variables/functions, PascalCase for classes)
- Prefer composition over inheritance for plugin architecture

## Code rules:
- **C++20** standard required
- **4 spaces** for indentation
- **120 character** line limit
- **snake_case** for variables and functions
- **PascalCase** for classes and namespaces

## Commit rules:
Examples:
- `feat(capture): add DXGI desktop duplication support`
- `fix(editor): resolve timeline crash on large projects`
- `docs(readme): update build instructions for Windows`
